          "title": "The impartial God who champions the powerless (10:17-19)",
          "body": "Verse 17 is one of the Old Testament's most compressed doxologies: God of gods, Lord of lords, great, mighty, awesome — four stacked divine titles that leave no competitor standing. But Moses immediately grounds that transcendence in two specific attributes: God does not show partiality and does not take a bribe. These are not abstract virtues; in the ancient Near East, both partiality and bribery were endemic to judicial systems where the wealthy could purchase favorable verdicts and the powerful could ignore the vulnerable. The God of Israel is constitutionally incapable of operating that way. Verse 18 moves the argument from what God refuses (partiality) to what He actively does: He executes justice for the orphan, the widow, and the alien. The three most legally vulnerable categories in Israelite society — those without a male kinsman to advocate for them — are the specific objects of God's active justice. Verse 19 draws the ethical inference: Israel must love the alien as God loves the alien, grounded in the lived memory that 'you were aliens in the land of Egypt.' Peter Davids notes that this triangular structure — God's character → God's action → Israel's required imitation — is the deepest pattern of Old Testament ethics, and its New Testament equivalent is John 13:34: 'as I have loved you, so you must love one another.'"
