        "number": 5,
        "title": "The God who champions the powerless — and demands Israel's imitation",
        "range": "10:17-19",
        "excerpt": "For the LORD your God is the God of gods and the Lord of lords…He executes justice for the orphan and the widow, and shows His love for the alien…So show your love for the alien, for you were aliens in the land of Egypt.",
        "body": "Verses 17-19 present the chapter's most practical ethical argument, moving from divine character through divine action to human obligation. The structure is precise: who God is (v. 17) determines what God does (v. 18), which determines what Israel must do (v. 19).\n\nVerse 17's doxological stacking — God of gods, Lord of lords, great, mighty, awesome — is not religious hyperbole but deliberate polemic against the ancient Near Eastern pantheon. In a world populated by local deities with territorial limits and susceptibility to bribery (ancient temples routinely served as sites where wealth could purchase divine favor), Moses asserts a God who transcends all such categories. *El gibbor ve-nora* — mighty God and awesome — echoes Isaiah 9:6 and anticipates Nehemiah 9:32. The specific negations of v. 17 — no partiality, no bribery — are not incidental: they attack the precise assumptions of ancient Near Eastern religion, where the gods favored the wealthy and could be appeased by gifts.\n\nVerse 18 then moves from what God refuses to what God does. He 'executes justice' (*oseh mishpat*) — the active, legally-charged verb — for the orphan, the widow, and the alien. These three categories constitute the most vulnerable triad in Israelite society: the fatherless child, the widowed woman, and the resident alien all lacked the male kinship network that provided legal standing and economic protection in ancient Israel. God is not neutral toward them; He advocates for them. And His advocacy is material — He gives the alien 'food and clothing,' the two irreducible necessities of bodily existence.\n\nVerse 19's 'so' is the ethical hinge: because God loves the alien this way, Israel must love the alien. The ground is not humanitarian sentiment but both theological (God's own character) and experiential ('you were aliens in the land of Egypt'). Israel's memory of Egyptian bondage is pressed into service as the raw material of ethical imagination: you know what it is to be the vulnerable foreigner dependent on the host society's mercy. Let that memory govern how you treat the foreigner in your midst. This is the pattern Jonathan Edwards identified as 'typological ethics' — Israel's historical experience becomes the moral ground for a required ethical posture. Peter Davids notes that this same triangular structure — divine character, divine action, human imitation — recurs in 1 John 4:11 ('since God so loved us, we also ought to love one another')."
